			<h1><span class="less"><a href="index.html">SLE 2011</a> paper:</span><br><i>Ambiguity Detection: Scaling to Scannerless</i></h1>
			<h2><a href="../profile/HendrikusJSBasten.html">Hendrikus J. S. Basten</a>, <a href="../profile/PaulKlint.html">Paul Klint</a>, <a href="../profile/JurgenVinju.html">Jurgen Vinju</a></h2>
<ul><li>DOI: <a href="https://doi.org/10.1007/978-3-642-28830-2_17">10.1007/978-3-642-28830-2_17</a></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t5b.html"><span class="tagM">T5B: Language Description Analysis</span></a><ul><li> The paper’s main goal is detecting ambiguity in language definitions using scannerless parsing.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t5f.html"><span class="tagL">T5F: Performance</span></a><ul><li> A key emphasis is scalability/performance when applying ambiguity detection at larger scale.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t4a.html"><span class="tagL">T4A: Workbenches</span></a><ul><li> The contribution is tied to parsing tooling and infrastructure for scannerless generalized parsing.
</li></ul></li></ul>
